I wrote this platform by consulting affordable housing advocates, tenants rights organizers, homelessness warriors, and housing experts. Not the CA Assoc. of Realtors or CA. Apt Assoc. It's backed by research, and based on the premise that housing should be a human right.

Part 4: Greenline Zoning. More housing in the wealthiest places in CA Balanced development of housing commensurate with job growth Prioritize 100% affordable housing development on publicly-owned surplus lands

This legislation will also include universal preference for anyone displaced from the area under Ellis Act and Owner Move-In evictions to allow people to return to the communities from which they were forced out.

An Anti-Displacement Act would require state and local agencies that approve developments to take into account any socioeconomic impacts a development may have on rental prices in the surrounding area.

Comm.'s experiencing gentrification & displacement need seats at the table when it comes to making land use policy that affects their livelihoods. This didn't happen with #SB50. Vulnerable comm's were an afterthought. It's why so many AH groups issued a letter today opposing.

Part 3: Alleviate Displacement & Gentrification $$$for low-income communities to create land use plans that address their specific needs An Anti-Displacement Act to complement CEQA, analyzing socioeconomic impacts of a development Repeal Article 34 for new public housing

The Costa-Hawkins Act has stripped cities throughout California of their ability to expand rent control policies that would provide relief to over 5 million renter households all across California. Meanwhile, the Ellis Act has legalized evictions for profit.
On average, an estimated 500,000 Californians face evictions every year so that landlords can raise rents and bring in higher-paying tenants.

Part 2: Universal Rent Control & Tenant Protections Repealing the Costa-Hawkins and Ellis Acts Universal right to legal counsel for anyone facing eviction Rental registry & landlord licensing structure to effectively regulate predation & speculation

Housing should be a human right. In order to ensure a California that’s truly affordable for all, not just those who can afford what the real estate market offers, we need to work toward decommodifying housing and build for need, not for profit.

The "density-first, social problems later" approach is a big reason why we've lost thousands of working class people of color in District 11. Yes, density, but also equity. This requires deep investments in housing that's affordable to no-to-low income households.

Transit-friendly, walkable, & dense communities should be available to ALL Californians, not just the wealthy. Wealthier newcomers often take more flights, use more carbon-intensive delivery services, and rideshares, etc. Lower income people have smaller carbon footprints.

Part 1: $100B California Housing Emergency Fund to Remove 200,000+ units from the speculative market Build 100,000+ new deeply affordable homes, prioritizing building along public transit lines and walkable places, built w/ union labor Rehab existing publicly housing
